#text: Desktop publishing software company Adobe

named a new CEO and posted strong fourth-quarter earnings. The company said it earned $127.5 million, or 34 cents a share, compared with $90 million, or 23 cents a share, during the year-ago quarter. Analysts polled by First Call had been expecting a gain of 29 cents a share. Total sales reached $355.2 million, vs. $281.8 million last year. The company named President Bruce Chizen to the additional posts of CEO and member of the board of directors. Chizen replaces John Warnock, who has now been named chief technology officer, a newly created position. Adobe shares were trading higher in after-hours to $57.74 on the Island ECN. The stock closed down $8.88 during the regular session at $57.31.

Headlines.Author: Barbara C. Costanza
Headlines.Headline: Verity reports and gives outlook
Headlines.BodyHeadline: Verity reports and gives outlook

#text: After market closed Wednesday, Verity Inc.

posted second-quarter earnings, along with commenting on its next quarters. Net income totaled $8.2 million, or 23 cents a share, beating the consensus estimate by 3 cents a share. In the year-ago period, the company earned $1.1 million, or 3 cents a share. Revenue totaled $34.5 million, up 107 percent compared with the $16.7 million reported in the year-ago period. For the second half of fiscal 2001, the company anticipates revenue will increase 9 to 11 percent on a sequential quarterly basis. Earnings will be between 23 cents and 25 cents a share for the third quarter and 24 cents to 27 cents for the fourth quarter. Analysts polled by First Call currently expect a profit of 22 cents and 23 cents, respectively. Revenue for the year will be in the range of $144.4 million and $146.6 million. Shares closed down 69 cents to $18.56.

shares could fall Wednesday morning due to the company’s third-quarter earnings warning. Headlines.Author: CBS.MarketWatch.com
Headlines.Headline: Annuity sellers cry foul

#text:
Sellers of annuities are complaining about the president's budget
    proposal. The Clinton plan calls for making most exchanges between annuities taxable,
    including the reallocation of assets within a variable annuity, the Wall Street Journal
    reported Wednesday. The plan undermines two main selling points: tax deferral and the
    ability to reallocate money within an annuity. There are two types of annuities. Variable
    annuities operate very much like mutual funds with investors paying no tax on gains until
    money is withdrawn. Fixed annuities are backed by corporate and government bonds and
    deliver a guaranteed rate of return. "This is a huge mistake," says

, an executive vice president for the industry's largest seller of
    annuities,
. Critics of annuities, however welcome the move.
with the

in Fairfax, VA sees the proposal
    driving "a stake right through the heart" of the industry. Hopewell, who never
    recommends annuities, believes high fees and commissions on the products make them less
    attractive than mutual funds. Should the proposal become law, the case for owning
    annuities "will be even worse," he concluded.
